<TEXT>
<P>
 THE HAT OF MY MOTHER by Max Steele (Algonquin Books of Chapel Hill: $9.95; 270 
pp.) . Available for the first paperback, Steele's short fiction offers solidly 
constructed plots, vivid characterizations and well-crafted sentences. The 
title story recounts the curious misadventures the narrator's prim mother 
encountered when she set out to buy a replacement for her antiquated favorite 
hat. In the multilayered "Another Love Story," a married man scrutinizes his 
former lover's successful books, hoping and fearing they contain some hint of 
their affair. Steele received the O. Henry Prize for "Color the Daydream 
Yellow," a vivid evocation of man's memories of an early love affair in Paris. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Column; Book Review 
