<HEADLINE>
<P>
SUMMER SPLASH; FOUR TOUR GUIDES SHOW YOU THE WAY; SLASH; A PINBALL-PLAYING 
COUCH POTATO 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By CHUCK CRISAFULLI, Chuck Crisafulli is a frequent contributor to Calendar. 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Some might think that a world-class rock 'n' roller like guitarist Slash of 
Guns N' Roses would spend the summer in sunny, nonstop debauchery. But the 
28-year-old rocker says that these days, maintaining a busy work schedule is 
more satisfying than pursuing summer pleasures.  
</P>
<P>
 "If I'm not working hard, I tend to get depressed," he says. "I like to work 
at a fast pace, and I try to avoid too much free time. I was supposed to take a 
break so my wife and I could take a trip for our first-year anniversary, and 
that was nine months ago. We're still in the planning stages." 
</P>
<P>
 Slash has plenty of work lined up for himself this summer. He's got a solo 
project ready to go into pre-production, and by August will be working with 
Guns N' Roses on the band's next album. There are some musical events coming to 
Los Angeles that may tempt him out of the studio, but GNR fans might be 
surprised by Slash's concert choices.  
</P>
<P>
 "Maybe it sounds odd coming from me, but I think Harry Connick Jr.'s great. 
I'd love to see him play. I'm a big Joe Walsh fan, so I'd love to see the 
Eagles. I think the Isley Brothers show would be very cool. And the Gipsy Kings 
are amazing. Leon Redbone's coming to town -- now there would a great show to 
get some guys together, leave the wives at home, order up some big steaks and 
listen to the man play."  
</P>
<P>
 It might also be hard to imagine Slash humming along to "Funny Girl," but the 
guitarist numbers himself among Barbra Streisand's admirers. He may not make 
her Anaheim Pond shows, though. "I'm a big fan of her work, and I'd love to see 
her perform, but her tickets are too expensive." 
</P>
<P>
 Slash says he would like to see Metallica and Alice in Chains at the Glen 
Helen Blockbuster Pavilion and may get out to catch James Brown's Greek Theatre 
show. "That's a show to see. You haven't really been belittled until you've 
been belittled by James Brown. I met him once and he sort of growled at me." 
</P>
<P>
 But he definitely won't be at summer shows by Phil Collins, Counting Crows, 
Foreigner, or, predictably, the Oak Ridge Boys. He gives Meat Loaf credit for 
being "the comeback story of the decade," but don't look for him at the big 
guy's Irvine Meadows concert.  
</P>
<P>
 Slash is a dedicated fan of movie monsters, so he says he may make it to 
Fangoria magazine's Weekend of Horrors next month at the L.A. Airport Hilton. 
"That's something I have to go to. I've been collecting 'Fango' since I was 14. 
I've got a huge stack of them in the garage." He takes his monsters seriously: 
He asked Stan Winston's shop (the group behind "Jurassic Park") to build him a 
dinosaur for his foyer, and he has a T. rex in his bathroom. 
</P>
<P>
 But the mega-hype surrounding this summer's movie releases hasn't gotten Slash 
any more excited about getting out to the multiplex. "There are some movies I 
love, but I hate going to the theaters. I usually just fall asleep. I know John 
Goodman put his heart and soul into 'The Flintstones,' but I'll wait for the 
video."  
</P>
<P>
 What Slash is really looking for this summer is a pinball exposition. He's an 
avid collector of pinball machines, and recently helped to design a special 
Guns N' Roses machine on which the player can activate the music of the band. 
"It's the loudest machine ever built," he claims proudly.  
</P>
<P>
 Slash concedes that there's plenty going on around town this summer, but says 
that if he's not toiling in the studio, he'll probably just be relaxing at 
home. "I don't go on picnics. I don't go out for a day at the beach. If 
anything, I might go to a local bar and talk to the bartender for a while. 
Mostly though, I'll be at home with my wife, probably watching TV. I've 
regressed to the point where cartoons, Comedy Central and cooking shows can 
keep me very happy."* 
</P>
</TEXT>
