<HEADLINE>
<P>
NEW RELEASES; IN BRIEF 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By LEONARD FEATHER 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 * * * * Frank Wess, "Tryin' to Make My Blues Turn Green," Concord 
Jazz."Surprise! Surprise!" is the name of one of the five Wess originals; it 
could well have been the title of the entire album, with its inventive use of 
the eight musicians, the sax and flute solos by Wess, and an unpredictable set 
of tunes that vary from gentle to jaunty and even to wistful (Kenny Burrell's 
"Listen to the Dawn," Bucky Pizzarelli's "Stray Horn"). The non-Wess charts, by 
Scott Robinson, round out a consistently diverting set. 
</P>
<P>
 Albums are rated on a scale of one star (poor), two stars (fair), three stars 
(good, recommended), four stars (excellent). LEONARD FEATHER 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Recording Review 
</P>
</TYPE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> LA052994-0060 </DOCNO>
<DOCID> 046279 </DOCID>
<SOURCE>
<P>
 Los Angeles Times 
</P>
</SOURCE>
<DATE>
<P>
May 29, 1994, Sunday, Home Edition 
</P>
</DATE>
<SECTION>
<P>
Calendar; Page 50; Calendar Desk 
</P>
</SECTION>
<LENGTH>
<P>
129 words 
</P>
</LENGTH>
<HEADLINE>
<P>
NEW RELEASES; IN BRIEF 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By ZAN STEWART 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 * * * * Hank Jones, "Upon Reflection," Verve. This sublime recording reunites 
the wondrous Jones musical family: the great pianist Hank performing on record 
for the first time in decades with his younger brother, drummer Elvin, playing 
the tunes of their late sibling, Thad.Such favorites as "A Child Is Born" and 
"Mean What You Say" and never-before-heard goodies such as the title track are 
given seamless, elegant interpretations. Hank's subtly opulent sound, issuing 
dancer-like lines of even, glossy notes, is backed by George Mraz's plump beat 
and Elvin's whooshy brush work -- he never picks up a stick. A classic. 
</P>
<P>
 Albums are rated on a scale of one star (poor), two stars (fair), three stars 
(good, recommended), four stars (excellent). ZAN STEWART 
</P>
