<HEADLINE>
<P>
TENNIS / NCAA CHAMPIONSHIPS; USC'S BLACK MOVES INTO SINGLES FINAL 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By Associated Press 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Top-seeded Wayne Black of USC and Mark Merklein of Florida advanced to the 
NCAA men's tennis singles finals Saturday. 
</P>
<P>
 Black, the No. 1 player in the country, eliminated Joakim Appelqvist of 
Mississippi, 6-4, 6-4, and Merklein defeated No. 2-seeded Marcus Hilpert of 
Arkansas, 6-4, 6-3. 
</P>
<P>
 Black will also be in the doubles final today as he and Jon Leach beat Andy 
Zurcher and Todd Wilson of Notre Dame, 6-7 (7-5), 6-3, 6-3. Black and Leach 
will face Mississippi State's Joc Simmons and Laurent Miquelard, who beat Chris 
Mahony and Pablo Montana of Tennessee, 6-3, 7-5 in the semifinals. 
</P>
<P>
 Merklein (37-5) beat Black (30-4), when they first met in February in the 
National Indoor Championship at Louisville, 4-6, 7-6, 7-6. 
</P>
<P>
 Merklein, the No. 4 national singles player, started strongly against Hilpert, 
going up 4-0 in the first set. "If I play the way I did today, I have a good 
shot at the title," Merklein said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
