<HEADLINE>
<P>
MORNING BRIEFING: WASHINGTON SOCCER FANS WILL HAVE TO DANCE IN THE AISLES 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By EARL GUSTKEY 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Soccer purists are unhappy about a Washington, D.C., Police plan to build a 
six-foot metal fence around the field at RFK Stadium for five World Cup games. 
</P>
<P>
 World Cup organizing officials have protested, but Deputy Police Chief Melvin 
Clark said that despite objections, his department still plans to build the 
fence. 
</P>
<P>
 Dave Jensen, Washington venue executive director, said soccer enthusiasm 
shouldn't be confused with crowd control problems. 
</P>
<P>
 Recalling Brazilian fans' samba displays on the field during a U.S. Cup '93 
match at RFK last summer, Jensen said: "That's what you want. That is soccer at 
its best. 
</P>
<P>
 "One thing I think you have to do here in America is not to confuse an 
expression of enthusiasm and a visceral soccer reaction with a movement toward 
hooliganism. There's a big difference. 
</P>
<P>
 "The expressions of excitement and of following the game are natural 
expressions to these people and not to be confused with insurrection." 
</P>
<P>
 Trivia time: What country has the best won-lost record in the World Cup? 
</P>
<P>
 Just a start?Kendra Hanes, softball coach and outfielder who didn't make the 
cut with the touring Silver Bullets, the women's baseball team, did make it 
with the Kentucky Rifles, a Class A minor league team. 
</P>
<P>
 The Rifles play in Pikeville, Ky., and begin their season on June 17. Rifle 
General Manager Mike Weisbart didn't deny that the signing of Hanes -- who has 
never played baseball -- was a publicity gimmick but also said his team might 
play a historic baseball role. 
</P>
<P>
 "This team and I believe strongly that someday there will be a woman in 
baseball, and the best way for that to happen is to start in the minors," 
Weisbart said. 
</P>
<P>
 "There are some very disturbing attitudes in baseball about women, and we 
think they need to be attacked." 
</P>
<P>
 Riddle: From Ed Schuyler of the Associated Press: What has more ads than the 
yellow pages and goes faster? 
</P>
<P>
 Answer: An Indy car. 
</P>
<P>
 Trivia answer: Brazil, 44-11-11 since 1930. 
</P>
<P>
 Quotebook: From Barry Flatman of the London Daily Express: "There is a lot of 
talk about players coming on the scene too early, but (Gabriela) Sabatini is 
someone who has been playing too long." EARL GUSTKEY 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Column 
</P>
</TYPE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> LA052994-0285 </DOCNO>
