<P>
ALASKA GOVERNOR SIGNS BILL ALLOWING CONCEALED GUNS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By Associated Press 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Gov. Walter J. Hickel has signed a bill allowing Alaska residents to carry 
concealed handguns, saying he weighed the concerns of police with those of 
citizens who want to protect themselves from criminals. 
</P>
<P>
 "Those that impressed me the most were the women who called and said they 
worked late and had to cross dark parking lots, and why couldn't they carry a 
concealed gun?" Hickel said from Fairbanks, where he signed the bill Friday. 
</P>
<P>
 Village public safety officers, who keep the peace in rural Alaska and are 
usually unarmed, had expressed concerns about a concealed-gun law. A provision 
was added to the bill to allow communities to vote to ban concealed guns. 
</P>
<P>
 Alaskans 16 and older may carry handguns openly without a permit. To carry 
concealed handguns legally, they must be 21, obtain a $125 permit and pass a 
gun safety course. 
</P>
