<HEADLINE>
<P>
TEEN FATALLY SHOT IN FRONT OF CROWDED FOUNTAIN VALLEY STUDIO 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By GREG HERNANDEZ, TIMES STAFF WRITER 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 A 17-year-old was shot repeatedly in front of a crowded karaoke studio early 
Saturday in a fatal attack that police said appeared to be gang-related. 
</P>
<P>
 The shooting was the first homicide this year in Fountain Valley. 
</P>
<P>
 The victim, whose name was not released pending notification of his relatives, 
was standing with a group of people in the parking lot of Elvis Karaoke 
Studios, 18914 Brookhurst St., when the shooting occurred at 12:50 a.m. 
</P>
<P>
 "The victim and his friends attempted to get into the karaoke studio, but it 
was so busy that night that they had to turn around," said Sgt. Dann Bean. 
"They were attempting to leave when the shooting took place." 
</P>
<P>
 Witnesses told police that three people in a light-colored Toyota Celica drove 
up to the studio's parking lot and provoked a confrontation. 
</P>
<P>
 They said a male passenger wearing a yellow bandanna over his face got out of 
the car, waved a gun around, yelled a gang name and exchanged words with the 
victim before opening fire, Bean said. 
</P>
<P>
 At least six bullets were fired, and the victim was struck in the torso, the 
abdomen, hand and calf. His companions took the teen-ager to Fountain Valley 
Regional Hospital and Medical Center, where he died a short time later. No one 
else was injured in the attack, although several people were standing near the 
victim. 
</P>
<P>
 The assailants drove away after the shooting and remain at large. 
</P>
<P>
 Police detectives, who were alerted by hospital officials about the shooting, 
interviewed people at the hospital and at the shooting scene, but the 
investigation has been hampered by "extremely uncooperative witnesses," Bean 
said. 
</P>
<P>
 "We started rounding up as many people as we could, but we weren't able to 
find out much of anything," he said. 
</P>
<P>
 Bean said the shooting has the trademarks of the drive-by shooting typical of 
Asian gangs. The shooter typically steps out of the car and makes contact with 
the victim before firing. 
</P>
<P>
 Law enforcement officials consider these shootings to be potentially more 
threatening to the general population than drive-by shootings committed by 
Latino gangs because Asian gangs don't claim neighborhoods, so the shootings 
can occur anywhere. 
</P>
<P>
 Last year, a similar drive-by shooting occurred at the Family Fun Center in 
Fountain Valley. A gunman fired six shots into a crowd and injured three 
teen-agers. 
</P>
<P>
 "These were similar situations, where the gunman gets out of the car and fires 
in a public place," Bean said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
